10709c30-a762-4a0d-a8b6-86b42d440702	5fa5690c-66fb-42ed-9325-c184ca033d64	1	o far. You've explored various types of machine learning, such as supervised and unsupervised learning. Ask yourself: How do these methods differ in terms of data requirements and learning objectives? Reinforcement learning, as you'll see, stands apart because it involves learning from interaction with an environment, much like the way humans learn from experience.\n\n---\n\n#### What is Reinforcement Learning?\n\n[Estimated duration: ~10 minutes]\n\nLet's begin by defining what reinforcement learning actually is. In essence, reinforcement learning is a type of machine learning where an agent learns to make decisions by taking actions in an environment to maximize some notion of cumulative reward. This is different from supervised learning, where the model learns from a labeled dataset, or unsupervised learning, where the model tries to find hidden patterns in data. \n\nConsider this: Imagine you're teaching a dog to fetch.	CONTENT	231	{"start_pos": 745, "end_pos": 1672, "length": 927}	2025-11-27 10:32:47.72538	2025-11-27 10:32:47.725384
bce6b650-c1cc-4f31-9caf-565ebc6e138c	5fa5690c-66fb-42ed-9325-c184ca033d64	2	vised learning, where the model learns from a labeled dataset, or unsupervised learning, where the model tries to find hidden patterns in data. \n\nConsider this: Imagine you're teaching a dog to fetch. You can't explicitly program the dog with every possible scenario it might encounter. Instead, you reward it with treats when it brings the ball back. Over time, the dog learns that fetching the ball leads to rewards. Similarly, in reinforcement learning, the agent learns a policy—a strategy of choosing actions based on states that maximize the reward over time.\n\nAsk yourself: How does this trial-and-error learning process compare to how you learn new skills? Think about learning to ride a bike. You fall, you get up, and eventually, through experience and feedback, you learn to balance and steer. \n\n---\n\n#### Key Concepts in Reinforcement Learning\n\n[Estimated duration: ~15 minutes]\n\nNow, let's break down the key components of reinforcement learning.	CONTENT	239	{"start_pos": 1472, "end_pos": 2431, "length": 959}	2025-11-27 10:32:47.978616	2025-11-27 10:32:47.97862
